<p>In the latest development, Iranian authorities imposed a nationwide internet blackout as protests over soaring living costs and a collapsing currency continued and spread across the country. Rights groups and media reports said the crackdown has involved mass arrests and deadly force in some areas, while the government has acknowledged the demonstrations and signaled tougher measures. Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei blamed the unrest on foreign influence and told President Trump to focus on problems in the United States. President Trump warned the U.S. would “get involved” if Iran’s leadership killed protesters, while Iran’s U.N. ambassador alleged the U.S., in coordination with Israel, helped turn peaceful protests violent.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/aiDcgOMumIzflriulECPFR9aCzBEa1Jh2Yn_C396mxv3d6vMXur35mf0YVxLvZ0yNT6ca-EeJdLQcSQ9Ws63-Blatu_LKOCwbklP96UdZooC' alt='People gather on the streets amid anti-government unrest in Tehran, Iran, in a still image from a social media video dated Jan. 8, 2026.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Hospitals strained: Iranian medical staff described overwhelmed hospitals as injuries mounted amid continuing demonstrations.</li><li>Protest scale: Protests have been reported in more than 170 locations across 25 provinces, with some coverage estimating participation in the hundreds of thousands.</li><li>Zahedan clash: In Zahedan, a city with a large Baluch minority population, a march after Friday prayers was met with gunfire that reportedly wounded several people.</li><li>Opposition appeals: Exiled figure Reza Pahlavi urged supporters to keep mobilizing, including calls for protesters to seize city centres, while President Trump said he would not meet Pahlavi and questioned whether supporting him would be appropriate.</li><li>Regime calculus: Analysts said Iran’s leaders are projecting defiance publicly, but the internal cost-benefit calculus of repression may be more fraught than in past crises.</li></ul><blockquote>He should pay attention to the state of his own country instead. - Ayatollah Ali Khamenei</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Iran’s Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei: He portrayed protesters as acting to please President Trump, called them “vandals” and “saboteurs,” and said authorities would not back down. (<a href='https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2026/01/09/iran-protests-khamenei-trump/'>The Washington Post</a>)</li><li>President Donald Trump: He said Iran was in “big trouble” and warned the U.S. would “get involved” if the regime killed protesters, while indicating that does not necessarily mean troops on the ground. (<a href='https://www.timesofisrael.com/trump-says-iran-in-big-trouble-us-will-get-involved-if-regime-kills-protesters/'>The Times of Israel</a>)</li><li>Iran’s U.N. Ambassador Amir Saeid Iravan: He wrote to the U.N. alleging the U.S., in coordination with Israel, bears responsibility for turning peaceful protests into violent acts. (<a href='https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/iran-protests-us-israeli-regime-violence-ambassador-un-letter/article70492536.ece'>The Hindu</a>)</li><li>Human rights monitors: They reported dozens killed and thousands detained during the unrest, offering casualty and arrest tallies that differ from official accounts. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1965993/iran-cuts-internet-amid-expanding-protests-over-economy-supreme-leader-tells-trump-to-focus-on-problems-in-us'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>International Crisis Group analyst (Ali Vaez): He described a serious political crisis and highlighted obstacles that, in his view, make a full revolution difficult despite the protests’ spread. (<a href='https://www.france24.com/en/iranian-regime-s-iron-fist-internet-blackout-as-protests-swell-to-hundreds-of-thousands'>France 24</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1965993/iran-cuts-internet-amid-expanding-protests-over-economy-supreme-leader-tells-trump-to-focus-on-problem